{
  "family": "Intramolecular Nitrile Oxide Cycloaddition",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "C=CCCC[C-]=[N+]O"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CC2CCON2C1"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [],
    "rationale": "This example shows the intramolecular 1,3-dipolar cycloaddition of a nitrile oxide with a terminal alkene. The substrate, hex-5-enenitrile oxide, is a simple, acyclic molecule containing the two required functional groups (nitrile oxide and alkene) connected by a flexible alkyl chain. The tether length is appropriate to form a stable, fused bicyclic isoxazoline product (hexahydro-3aH-cyclopenta[d]isoxazole) via a 5-exo-trig cyclization, which is a common and favorable pathway for this reaction. The reaction is presented as the direct transformation of the nitrile oxide intermediate to the product, as the generation of the nitrile oxide from a precursor (like an oxime or nitroalkane) is a separate step and not part of the core cycloaddition.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple aliphatic substrate to avoid overlap with reactions involving aromatic systems. It avoids complex functional groups, heteroatoms (other than the N-O of the isoxazoline), or other reactive motifs that could trigger different named reaction classifications. The core transformation is clearly the intramolecular cycloaddition of a nitrile oxide and an alkene, making it a specific and unambiguous example for the INOC family."
  }
}
